Across the country, Bolivia's landlocked coastline memorial, lost to Chile in bloody conflicts in the 19th century, is still in its freshest memory - along with its desire to sail the Pacific again.
These are perhaps the strongest hopes in decades, now that Bolivia is awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice in The Hague on 1 October after five years of litigation.
“Bolivia has the power, the unification and the humility, and of course it is waiting for the verdict with a positive mind,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the ruling of the International Court of Justice on large screens across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule Bolivia in favor of their claim that Chile is obliged to grant Bolivia access to the sea, after decades of difficult negotiations.
