“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court ruled in favor of Bolivia, and that it would change little if he did.
The court, which is headquartered in the Netherlands, has no authority to grant land from Chile and has provided that the ruling will not affect the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the court’s ruling comes just six months after the final hearings indicates that the case “had not been complicated,” said Paz Sárate, a Chilean international law expert.
It is also possible that the past four years have not been an issue for Bolivia to advance, but have caused the country to return.
