At the moment, languages, as an elective language, are placed in the same place as scientific learning materials (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in private school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that for the reasons employers stated that it was difficult to recruit, it was 17 percent because of a lack of people with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future jobs.
Now that more and more jobs require language skills, this skill is essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career career people choose, it will have a real advantage in the future if they learn another language, which is a skill that lasts a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person an advantage over the competitors.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov on over 4,000 adults in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak another language well enough to sustain a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, or 15 percent.
