Although Ri has repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "staged" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded for every step it took, his statement seemed special in the sense that he did not deny unilateral nuclear disarmament.
Ri referred to the joint statements made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting between acting US Presidents and North Korean leaders in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work on the "nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump issued a pledge to ensure North Korea's security.
North Korea has sought a solution to formally end the Korean War in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must leave its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax a strict trade ban on North Korea.
“The United States demands that ‘nuclear disarmament occurs first’ and increases the pressure by using trade bans to achieve its goal, and even protests the declaration to end the war,” Ri said.
“There are only dreamers who don’t know anything about us who think that business beans can bring us to our knees.
