Ri did not mention any plans for another meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader spoke about at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister spoke of three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-In, South Korea's leader for the past five months, adding: "If the party involved in this nuclear weapons issue were South Korea instead of the United States, then this stalemate in the nuclear weapons issue would not be the nuclear weapons issue."
Despite this, the tone in Ri’s speech was very different from his speech last year when he said at the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target missiles from North Korea to the mainland of the United States after “the devil’s president” Trump called Kim a “missile man” in suicide.
