Harvard students take classes for a long time
A new course at Harvard University has given all students more sleep in an effort to counter the growing tendency of students to wake up and learn all night with the help of caffeine tablets.
A study found that students at the best university in the world often know little or nothing about thinking about themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and the Women’s Hospital, designed the course and believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea to do the course after giving a lecture on the effect that sleep deprivation has on learning ability.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why is this being said to me for the first time now, in my final year?’
She said no one had told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleeping habits help learning ability and performance in sports and even contribute to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the school’s director of health care, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were extremely sleepy over the week.
The course is an hour long and includes a variety of interactive tasks.
In one part is a picture of a room in a homestay, where students click on a cup of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how performance in sports can worsen during lack of sleep, as well as the importance of a good routine for sleep.
In another section, participants are told how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Maps of the school area with interactive symbols then encourage participants to think about their daily habits.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students.
But we feel they have a right to know this, just as a person has a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that honors those who wake up and learn all night is still present, he said, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Assurance of getting enough sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid obesity, because sleep deprivation increases the call of the brain for food so that the body is starving.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemistry and physics from California, helped Professor Czeisler put the course together, who was one of the professor’s choirs last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to call for a course for all students in the school.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all master students to complete a similar course before they start studying at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm clock, which reminds them to go to sleep, and to wake them, and keep in mind the damaging effects of blue light emitted by electronic displays and LED lights, which can confuse the internal clock of the body and lead to trouble with falling.
