Syria 'ready' for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for refugees to return voluntarily to the country and seek help to rebuild the country, which is now in a bad condition after seven years of war.
Foreign Minister Walid al Moualem spoke at the United Nations General Assembly and said the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer, thanks to the success of the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to bring about normal conditions by building areas that were completely destroyed by terrorists.
Everything is now ready for refugees to return voluntarily to the country they were forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic decisions that targeted their daily lives and jobs.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
An additional six million people who still live in the country need help.
Al-Moualem said Syrian authorities would be happy to accept aid to rebuild the country.
However, he stressed that they would not accept aid subject to conditions or assistance from countries that supported the rebellion.
