Latest news of algal bloom: Concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Latest news from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in the concentration of algae blossoms in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, worn-out algae blossoms are reported in certain areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota Charlotte and Collier counties - suggesting decreased concentrations.
The algae flower covers about 200 kilometres of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Unique flowers can be found about 16 miles from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
Algae blooms have also been reported in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations at or near Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, very low to high concentrations in Manatee County, very low to high concentrations at or near Sarasota County, very low concentrations at or near the coast of Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in the northwestern part of Florida over the past week.
